Two strings s and t are isomorphic if: Each character in s maps to exactly one character in t. No two different characters in s map to the same character in t.
The order of characters must be preserved. A character can map to itself.

two maps:
The first ensures consistency (a always maps to x)
The second prevents two different characters mapping to the same character

If lengths of s and t are different, return false
Create two HashMaps
Loop through each character: If mapping exists, verify it matches.
If mapping does not exist: Check reverse map to prevent duplicate mapping.
Store both mappings and if no conflicts occur, return true

class Solution {
    public boolean isIsomorphic(String s, String t) {
        if (s.length() != t.length()) return false;
        HashMap<Character, Character> mapST = new HashMap<>();
        HashMap<Character, Character> mapTS = new HashMap<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
            char chS = s.charAt(i);
            char chT = t.charAt(i);
            if (mapST.containsKey(chS)) {
                if (mapST.get(chS) != chT)
                    return false;
            } else {
                if (mapTS.containsKey(chT))
                    return false;
                mapST.put(chS, chT);
                mapTS.put(chT, chS);
            }}       
        return true;}
}
